						               													<description>The world is very confusing. It's good if you then have a clear picture of the enemy! Stage your image of the enemy with the right campaign for the right target group and clear away the image of the enemy in a politically correct manner.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;&amp;quot;Feindbild&amp;quot; (&amp;quot;Enemy stereotype&amp;quot;) - this is a unique game concept in which the fun of the game scratches the satire. The game can be explained in a few minutes. But you can play it for years. Provided, of course, that our enemy stereotypes do not change by then.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;Every player gets a target group to work for. Then five images of the enemy are laid out. And then it is important to stage the enemy images with the right media campaign in such a way that the anger of your own target group begins to boil. And that's about it. Isn't it nice when card games can be explained so easily?&amp;#10;&amp;#10;As enemy images there are the bad Russians, the classic terrorists, the scruffy social parasite, the greedy pharmaceutical industry and the corrupt European politician. And of course many more. The target groups are the conservatives, the left and the right and of course the totally confused aluminum hat wearers. And as campaigns there is the regulars' table, the focus on television and the daily press. And of course the satirical portals themselves. That closes the circle.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;As is usual with card games, you have to spend money on &amp;quot;Feindbild&amp;quot; in order to play it. Yes, we live in evil capitalism. Another enemy image. The game consists of 106 cards, which consist of 18 enemy images, 8 target groups and 80 campaigns. And there are also instructions for use.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;</description>
